According to the standard convention for exponentiation,\\
\[2^{2^{2^2}} = 2^{\left(2^{\left(2^2\right)}\right)} = 2^{16} = 65,\!536.\]If the order in which the exponentiations are performed is changed, how many <u>other</u> values are possible?\\
\\
$ \textbf{(A)}\ 0 \qquad \textbf{(B)}\ 1 \qquad \textbf{(C)}\ 2 \qquad \textbf{(D)}\ 3 \qquad \textbf{(E)}\ 4$
